# Dairo + Next.js (App Router)

This starter was scaffolded by `dairo init next`. It includes a configured Dairo
SDK client, an outbound send route, and an inbound webhook handler that verifies
delivery signatures.

## Files

- `lib/dairo.ts` — the configured `Dairo` client (`new Dairo({ apiKey })`).
- `app/api/dairo/send/route.ts` — `POST /api/dairo/send`, sends an email.
- `app/api/dairo/webhook/route.ts` — `POST {{inbox_route}}`, the inbound handler.

## 1. Set your API key

Copy `.env.example` to `.env.local` and fill in the values:

```sh
cp .env.example .env.local
```

```text
DAIRO_API_KEY=dairo_...
DAIRO_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_...
```

`DAIRO_API_KEY` authenticates outbound sends. `DAIRO_WEBHOOK_SECRET` is the
`whsec_...` value returned when you create the webhook (next step).

## 2. Install and run

```sh
{{install_cmd}}
npm run dev
```

## 3. Register the webhook

Expose your local server with a tunnel (e.g. `ngrok http 3000`) and register the
public URL with Dairo:

```sh
dairo webhook create --url https://<your-tunnel>{{inbox_route}} --event {{webhook_event}}
```

For local development without a public URL, use the Dairo CLI's inbound sandbox,
which re-POSTs live events to your local route and signs them so this handler
verifies them unchanged:

```sh
dairo listen --forward-to http://localhost:3000{{inbox_route}}
```

`dairo listen` prints an ephemeral signing secret on startup — set it as
`DAIRO_WEBHOOK_SECRET` so the handler verifies forwarded events.

## 4. Send a test email

```sh
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/dairo/send \
  -H 'content-type: application/json' \
  -d '{"inboxId":"<inbox-id>","to":"you@example.com","text":"hello from dairo init"}'
```

## Webhook signature verification

Dairo signs the **raw request body**, so the handler reads `await req.text()`
before parsing JSON and passes those exact bytes to `verifyWebhookRequest`. Do
not verify re-serialized JSON — the bytes (and therefore the signature) will not
match.
